{"cursor":"6326","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{multiple issues|\n\n\n\n}}\n\n {{Infobox Jewish leader |honorific-prefix =\nRabbi |name = Asher Wade |image = |caption = |denomination= Orthodox Judaism\n|semicha = Ohr Somayach, Jerusalem |rabbi = |birth_name = Wallace S. Wade\n|birth_date = |birth_place = Danville, Virginia |death_date = |death_place =\n|buried = |nationality = |residence = Jerusalem |parents = |spouse = |children =\n|occupation = Psychotherapist |profession = |employer = |alma_mater = |signature\n= |website = [http://www.asherwade.com/ www.asherwade.com/] }} 'Rabbi Dr. Asher\nWade' is an American-born international lecturer, college instructor and\npsychotherapist. He was also well known as a \"must have\" tour-guide at Yad\nVashem, the Holocaust museum in Israel, from Jan. 1991 until Nov. 2005.\n\nAlthough there have been a number of Christian clergy who have become converts\nto Judaism, Asher Wade is one of the few who have gone on to become an orthodox\nrabbi. As an ordained Methodist minister, Asher Wade and his wife were moved by\nthe articles in a Sunday morning newspaper commemorating the 40th Anniversary of\nKristallnacht. At that time, he was attending the University of Hamburg in\nGermany working towards his doctorate in the field of Metaphysics and Relativity\nTheory. [http://www.simpletoremember.com/vitals-\n/asherwade.htm Asher Wade's Story ]\n\nHe had already earned a B.A. in Philosophy in America and a Master's degree in\nPhilosophical Theology at the University of Edinburgh in Scotland. In addition,\nhe had previously interned as an adolescent and marriage counselor at the U.S.\nArmy Chaplaincy Center in Berlin while he was attending the Goethe Institute for\nGerman studies.\n","linknr":187,"url":"Asher_Wade","recorded":1375089018,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Asher_Wade&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Asher_Wade&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.o